<div id="review_536849557" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/536849557" />
    <a title="G.E. Beyers" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14080401-g-e-beyers"><img alt="G.E. Beyers" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1613215890p2/14080401.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/536849557?book_show_action=true">Feb 15, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="G.E. Beyers" class="user" itemprop="url" name="G.E. Beyers" href="/user/show/14080401-g-e-beyers">G.E. Beyers</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">children 8-12</span></div>

          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to G.E. by: </span>
      Casey Sean Harmon
  </div>


    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer536849557" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1670320303871914668">I loved this book, and loved Casey Sean Harmon&apos;s old fashioned style of writing. Took me back to my Enid Blyton days, when children&apos;s literature was pretty light hearted and there was a strong moral theme running through most. I enjoyed the plot, the characters were endearing, and the varied array of creatures living in Everafter kept the imagination flowing. <br/><br/>For storyline, plot content, character build and flow I would actually have rated this 5 star but I dropped it to 4 as a couple of things </span>
  <span id="freeText1670320303871914668" style="display:none">I loved this book, and loved Casey Sean Harmon's old fashioned style of writing. Took me back to my Enid Blyton days, when children's literature was pretty light hearted and there was a strong moral theme running through most. I enjoyed the plot, the characters were endearing, and the varied array of creatures living in Everafter kept the imagination flowing. <br /><br />For storyline, plot content, character build and flow I would actually have rated this 5 star but I dropped it to 4 as a couple of things bothered me. Firstly editing. Mistakes grate on me when I read a book and can stop me in my tracks if I have to work out what the problem is, therefore ruining the flow of the story for me. <br />In 'Sun dog' the author uses a portion of another chapter 'Poor Clovensport', but the two versions are completely different. Right at the point where the pirate cuts his own ear off on the bridge and falls into the abyss below. I had to go back and check the content in 'Sun dog' because I had already read that part and in my head it had registered differently, so reading it for a second time and finding a huge variance was rather disconcerting. Having said that, a child may not notice the difference. <br /><br />Another thing I noticed was the the fact that it's listed as a YA novel, the main characters are 13 and 15 (with Susan the youngest being 6) but the style of writing is very much suited to Middle grade 8-12 year olds I would say. Again, only my personal opinion. <br /><br />Other than these two things I would say it's up there with the best of good children's books. I liked the fact that the children were respectful of each other, and it was a cute twist with Clovensport becoming the pirate king. The ending was also nice with the absentee parents deciding to spend a bit of quality time with the kids.<br /><br />All in all an excellent story, well written with great characters and a good plot. I will definitely be reading 'The tree of malice' when it comes out, and will be ordering both 'Reign of the night creatures' and 'Tree of malice' for my nephew.<br /> </span>
  <a data-text-id="1670320303871914668" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

