<div id="review_647835310" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/647835310" />
    <a title="Richard" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6675686-richard"><img alt="Richard" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1320329123p2/6675686.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/647835310?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Richard" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Richard" href="/user/show/6675686-richard">Richard</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6675686-richard?shelf=fantasy">fantasy</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6675686-richard?shelf=middle-grade">middle-grade</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6675686-richard?shelf=giveaway-wins">giveaway-wins</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer647835310" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15469545230925558435">In full disclosure I won this book in a Goodreads giveaway.<br/><br/>This was a quick and simple story. It reminded me somewhat of traditional books that I read when I was younger such as the Chronicles of Narnia or Peter Pan, where a group of brothers and sisters are whisked of to a magical land and have an adventure. <br/><br/>There were a few points that were unbelievable, unrealistic, inconsistent or where logic seemed to go out of the window, but for the most part I think these were only noticeable as an adult</span>
  <span id="freeText15469545230925558435" style="display:none">In full disclosure I won this book in a Goodreads giveaway.<br /><br />This was a quick and simple story. It reminded me somewhat of traditional books that I read when I was younger such as the Chronicles of Narnia or Peter Pan, where a group of brothers and sisters are whisked of to a magical land and have an adventure. <br /><br />There were a few points that were unbelievable, unrealistic, inconsistent or where logic seemed to go out of the window, but for the most part I think these were only noticeable as an adult reading the book and would probably not be noticed by a child.<br /><br />I enjoyed the fact that the siblings were kind and caring to each other, I also liked the strong moral theme throughout the book, emphasizing the importance of doing the right thing and working well with others.<br /><br />I loved the twist to do with the dog, <a class="jsShowSpoiler spoilerAction">(view spoiler)</a><span class="spoilerContainer" style="display: none">[ he turns out to be the pirate captain. <a class="jsHideSpoiler spoilerAction">(hide spoiler)</a>]</span> and thought it was a really clever idea that was well executed.<br /><br />The characters were interesting and fun, but as you would expect for a book aimed at a younger audience they are lacking in depth. Generally speaking day-time creatures and people are good and always do good things, and night-time creatures and people are evil and only do evil things. I would like to have learnt more about the characters thoughts and what motivates them especially Viktor and Prophet, who we only learn a little bit about.<br /><br />The creatures in the book are typical creatures found in fantasy novels, especially those from Greek mythology such as griffins, centaurs, dragons, phoenixes and a giant octopus.<br /><br />The book is presented in a lovely way; there are a few pictures throughout, generally showing the characters in the story. The footers on each page as well as the breaks that show a change in the POV are artistically done.<br /><br />Personally I would say this book was aimed at the younger end of a middle-grade audience (8 to 10 year olds).<br /><br />The ending was lovely and a good lesson for parents as well as children.<br /><br />I gave this book 4 out of 5, I probably would really rate it as 3 ½ in terms of how much I enjoyed it. But my ranking reflects how much I think I would have enjoyed it if I was in the target age group.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15469545230925558435" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

